Since you have said that e.g. `RealN extends ComplexN`, you don&#39;t need do have separate `(Complex, Real)` methods, for example.  All you need is

```
    static ComplexN add(ComplexN c1,ComplexN c2) { ... }
    static RealN add(RealN r1, RealN r2) { ... }
    static RationalN add(RationalN r1, RationalN r2) { ... }
    static IntegerN add(IntegerN i1, IntegerN i2) { ... }
    static NaturalN add(NaturalN i1, NaturalN n2) { ... }
```

You don&#39;t need any more methods than that.  If you call `add` with a `ComplexN` and a `RealN` value, then this will just treat the `RealN` value as its supertype `ComplexN`, which is the correct behavior.

